docs/business-process.md:73:1. **A customer request** — a retail buyer asks sales for a specific product type, format, or a refresh of an existing line. Sales relays the brief to the PM.
docs/business-process.md:74:2. **An internal line refresh** — the company decides on its own to refresh a line (new designs, new licensors or properties, a new product category) and presents it to buyers afterward.
docs/business-process.md:75:3. **New product development** — the team develops a brand-new product format or category into a full concept before seeking buyer interest.
docs/business-process.md:77:Where the *ideas* come from (Jessica): "a shopping trip to one of the retailers our client or we want it to be, an offer from a factory, inspiration from internet, a mix from existent product formats we already have."
docs/business-process.md:91:**An offer (a "project").** One offer, to one buyer, at one retailer, for one season. For example: *"Julie Greer at Burlington for Valentines 2027,"* or *"Alice Zhu at Dollar General for Fall/Winter 2026."* An offer carries the **brief**: the buyer, the retailer, the season, which licensors and properties are in play, which product types the buyer wants, the on-shelf date, and any restrictions. It exists so the creative team has a single reference and doesn't have to memorize the details. As Jessica put it, "each buyer purchases certain types of products and specific properties within each license. All this information is included… as a brief so the creative designer can refer to it during the process."
docs/business-process.md:95:**A picked product (a "SKU").** When a buyer selects a design from a presentation, that selection becomes a specific product to be built, carried all the way through approval and production. A picked product carries: its full approval history, its link back to the offer it came from, its licensor submission numbers, its sample photos, and the order history of which retailers bought it and when.
docs/business-process.md:97:There is also a third, quieter category the business currently *loses*: **the preliminary designs that were shown to a buyer but not picked.** These are real creative work, but today they vanish (see §10 — this is the company's single biggest pain point).
