docs/business-process.md:176:The problem: the **manufacturing constraints** — die lines, the number of colors a factory can print, the printing technique, where legal lines must be placed — are often **known only to the art director**, who "usually specifies the restrictions, but sometimes forgets to share them with the creative team, or sometimes she's unaware of them." The mismatch is then discovered during sampling, forcing the design and licensing sheet to be redone. When both the creative and technical designers understand the product-type constraints up front (based on the agreed factory cost), products go through with far fewer revisions.
docs/business-process.md:206:## 9. Reuse, multi-buyer dynamics, and closure
docs/business-process.md:208:**Selling the same product to more than one buyer.** Most licensors allow a product to be sold to multiple buyers over time. **Some buyers prohibit resale** of what they've bought — a restriction the business must respect per buyer. There is also a **time constraint** on re-offering. Today reuse happens only case-by-case and only occasionally, when someone remembers the product exists. The product keeps its identity (its code is the licensor's approval record) and should carry the history of which retailers ordered it.
docs/business-process.md:210:**Two buyers pick the same design at once.** When this happens, the team notices manually. The fix: the creative designer makes a **second version with minor changes** (different icons, image sizes, colors, or embellishments), and sales presents the variation to one of the two buyers — without explaining the real reason.
docs/business-process.md:213:- the factory quote doesn't meet the company's cost target (**cost**),
docs/business-process.md:216:- the buyer declined and no other buyer is interested (**buyer**).
docs/business-process.md:220:**Approved-but-unsold concepts.** A large pool of concepts get licensor approval but then stall — the buyer passed on price, the production timing didn't fit, or the order was canceled. These are **not dead**; they are approved inventory that should be re-offered to buyers, but today the work is effectively wasted because nobody re-surfaces it.
docs/business-process.md:224:**1. Lost preliminary designs — the #1 pain point.** Designs shown to a buyer but not picked are tied to that one buyer's presentation and effectively disappear. *"Designs that are lost are lost several times a week. We've tried to reuse these designs for other projects… but it involves manually searching through past presentations"* (Jessica). The team only ever organizes what was *selected*; the rest is lost creative work.
docs/business-process.md:244:- **The business gets ahead of the season instead of scrambling.** *"Project management should be proactive, not reactive… Instead of waiting for a buyer to request products for next year's Valentine's Day or Christmas and then scrambling, we should have offered the products beforehand"* (Jessica). The company already knows its seasons — Valentine's, Easter, Graduation, Back to School, Harvest, Halloween, Christmas, plus Everyday — and its history of which buyers order what. Approved-but-unsold concepts should be proactively packaged into seasonal offers.
docs/business-process.md:253:*Spruce Line (formerly "Edge") is the company's non-licensed, original-design business. There is no licensor anywhere in this process — the only external approval is the buyer's.*
docs/business-process.md:259:**A design collection (a trend/art theme).** A body of original art on a theme — "Gaming," "Farmhouse," "Cowgirl Country," "Soft Religion" — that is **available to all accounts**, not tied to any one buyer. Collections are organized by format and then by theme (e.g., under "Wall Art": Gaming, Farmhouse, Kitchen Art, Sneaker Art, Automotive, Florals, Coastal, Abstracts, and many more; under "Floor Coverings": Coir Mats, Spring Coir Mats, Holiday Coir Mats). A single trend collection can hold **hundreds of designs**, and the **high-resolution art isn't even produced until a buyer asks for it.** Collections are the raw creative inventory; they are not yet products.
docs/business-process.md:261:**A project (account-specific work).** One project for one buyer/account — for example, "Forman Mills, buyer Jennifer, Wall Art" or "Burlington, buyer Anna, New Formats." A project is where a specific buyer's selections and brief live.
docs/business-process.md:263:**A style-numbered product.** When a buyer actually commits — selects specific designs and either places an order or requests a sample — those selections become **style-numbered products**. The style number is the product's permanent identity, and all of that product's files are findable by it. **Only style-numbered items are "real products."** The hundreds of designs in a trend collection are not.
