docs/business-process.md:275:| 7 | **Style number assigned (commitment)** | Jen + team | Once the buyer commits to a size/format and an order (or a sample for sample-accounts), each selection gets a **style number** — it becomes a real product. |
docs/business-process.md:276:| 8 | **Costing** | Design → Albert/China → Adam | Design makes a costing tech pack; Albert and the China team handle factory selection and costing; **Adam reviews and approves the costing**. |
docs/business-process.md:278:| 10 | **Order → production** | Factory (via Yuchen) | When there's an order, the team waits for **Yuchen's email** with the factory deadline, then preps and sends files for production. |
docs/business-process.md:280:**Approvals are entirely internal + buyer.** Jen finalizes; Adam gets buyer sign-off on art changes; once the buyer approves and an order is placed, it goes to production. **Jen and Mal review artwork and tech packs**; Jen handles purchase-order review for accuracy; Mal handles sample-request approvals. There is no licensor anywhere.
docs/business-process.md:284:The unit of work after a buyer meeting depends on the account. Two real examples (Jen):
docs/business-process.md:286:- **Burlington (buyer Anna) — no samples.** Meeting → selections document → Anna uses it to make her final selections for an order → **only then** are style numbers assigned. This account never gets samples.
docs/business-process.md:287:- **Hobby Lobby (buyer Kyle) — samples required.** Meeting → selections document → the team internally picks a size and format → Kyle approves or requests changes → style numbers are assigned → **samples are requested.**
docs/business-process.md:289:Most trend collections are **not** account-specific — **except all storage designs and all Hobby Lobby work**, which are. This account-by-account variation is exactly why Jen organizes her work by **lifecycle stage** rather than by buyer: at a glance she needs to see where each piece of work is and what the next step is.
docs/business-process.md:295:**Cancellation.** The most common reason a Spruce design never reaches production is simply that **the buyer doesn't move forward** — projects sit "with the buyer for approval" for weeks or months. Adam and Jen review the full list **once a quarter** and remove the stalled ones. As with POP, there's no formal cancel step.
docs/business-process.md:297:**Reuse.** Design collections are reused across all accounts by design — that's their entire purpose. Once something is a style-numbered product it belongs to a specific buyer, and multi-buyer reuse isn't tracked the way it is in POP.
docs/business-process.md:299:**Reactive vs. proactive.** Usually the buyer reviews themes the company has already developed and selects from them; occasionally a buyer asks for a specific theme the company doesn't have yet (e.g., "Bears with Sweaters").
docs/business-process.md:307:- **No timeline tracking.** The design team doesn't track order timelines at all; the only hard date is the factory deadline that arrives in Yuchen's email. Buyers (especially Burlington) often place orders at the last minute, leaving little prep time.
docs/business-process.md:318:Her model of a frictionless account is **Ollies**: the buyer buys everything he selects, works in a single format (canvas), pricing already exists, and he communicates well. The more the process can make every account behave like that, the better.
docs/business-process.md:326:Although POP and Spruce run different processes, they share people (Adam in sales; Albert and the China team for costing and factories; Yuchen for factory deadlines), share product development (but never artwork), and suffer several of the **same underlying process ailments**:
docs/business-process.md:331:| **Stalled work piles up with no formal closure** | approved-but-unsold concepts; products open 4–5 years | projects sit "with buyer" for months; quarterly manual cull |
docs/business-process.md:334:| **Constraints/pricing surface too late** | manufacturing constraints known only to the art director | factory pricing changes hidden until sampling |
docs/business-process.md:335:| **Sales needs a clean status picture** | "list of all projects for the same retailer" | "a list for Adam on the exact status of all projects" |
docs/business-process.md:346:- **Project / offer** — one offer to one buyer at one retailer for one season (POP); one account-specific body of work (Spruce).
docs/business-process.md:354:- **On-shelf date** — when a product must be in stores. **PPS-requested date** — when a buyer wants to see the physical sample (often weeks earlier). Two different deadlines.
docs/business-process.md:355:- **Costing sheet** — the document that establishes what a product will cost to make, built before factory quotes.

